<p>Of course, most people here get that the GOP is not ultimately going to enact policies that will back up their promises to fix the problem, but most voters don't get that.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the Democrats put out confusing messaging about being for the little guy and then turn around and don't follow through on it, either. &nbsp;Mark Pryor who is a Clintonian creation came out <i>against</i> the minimum wage increase ballot initiative in Arkansas while Cotton supported the measure - and won - he came off as a more in touch with "The People" candidate. &nbsp;That's just one example from this past go round. &nbsp;</p>
<p>I know everyone likes to say that the demographics favor Democrats, but favorable demographics do not guarantee that people in those demos will believe Democrats who are clearly attempting to hedge rather than offering policies that are clearly helpful to voters. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Anyway, the GOP is being very strategic and they are trying to steal the traditional mantle of the Democratic Party. &nbsp;I have to give them credit because unlike the Dems they always try to make sure that there's nothing left on the table for their opponents.</p>

