<p>Sarah Palin scared me for about an hour because of those women, but after I heard her speak, I knew those women wouldn't buy into her. &nbsp;What I didn't predict was how much disdain they ended having for Palin - I mean I felt that way about her and very angry with the McCain camp for trying to fool American women by picking a "random skirt" - but those women felt the same way in the end, too.</p>
<p>I had to hold my tongue and not give the lecture about voting for women just because they were women in the initial conversations and Palin basically proved my point without my having to make it in the end.</p>
<p>Anyway, I do know women who are not Democrats who probably would vote for her in part because she if she won she would have broken a glass ceiling for all of us.</p>
<p>I have a &nbsp;very close friend who is a life long Republican and she voted for Obama both times. &nbsp;It will be interesting to hear her thoughts as this election unfolds.</p>
<p>The other thing to consider is the fact that if the GOP does ultimately anoint Jeb Bush, the Republicans might have a similar challenge that we might have with Clinton in that they have some Bush Family fatigue amongst their ranks much like the Clinton fatigue amongst ours. &nbsp;You may see depressed turnout on both sides. &nbsp;</p>

