<p>Risks that frankly the Dean example does not reflect because when Dean was running, Americans were very happy about the war and blood-thirsty for revenge. &nbsp;Bush reflected their anger.</p>
<p>Should we get into Kerry at this point with his "for before he was against" nonsense? &nbsp;And you know what? &nbsp;His problem wasn't that he changed his position, his problem was that he sounded like a jerk when he took that passive-aggressive, lame approach to talking about his change of heart, he sounded disingenuous. &nbsp;Haltingly so, I might add.</p>
<p>It really wouldn't hurt Democrats to make a declarative statement or two when they would be on solid ground doing so even if they believe that there would be blowback. &nbsp;The freaking Republicans never worry about the fact that they are promoting fantasy - often in "angry" and passionate frames. &nbsp;They do really well at the polls these days.</p>
<p>I am really tired of all of these dry powder Democrats who pretend that their alchemy is a recipe for success. &nbsp;Obama was elected twice, but his ability to be really effective will end up being limited to two short years over the course of <i>eight</i> because of this erroneous theory that Democrats and black people need to check their passion and keep their powder dry. &nbsp;That's not only offensive, but also ineffective politics.</p>

