<li id="c300">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55618101">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">It also won't hunt </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55618101#c300?mode=alone;showrate=1#c300">10+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:103993">jhop7</a>, <a href="/user/uid:17036">Creosote</a>, <a href="/user/uid:116838">elwior</a>, <a href="/user/uid:25604">wishingwell</a>, <a href="/user/uid:191">Bob Johnson</a>, <a href="/user/uid:160769">McWaffle</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1130446">WI Lurker</a>, <a href="/user/uid:37824">inclusiveheart</a>, <a href="/user/uid:139379">J M F</a>, <a href="/user/uid:62874">mightymouse</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>since very few of us belong to unions. Don't get me wrong, there's a need for stronger unions rather than fewer or weaker unions. But lots of working people can be deluded into thinking that unions are the problem - I know several of them, including blue collar types in my own family. The GOP can paint unions as a cause for dropping wages, without irony, and a big portion of the electorate will say "what's a union?" The Democratic Party needs to strengthen unions and remind people why they exist, but an electoral strategy that depends too much on labor is an anachronism right now.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
“If the misery of the poor be caused not by the laws of nature, but by our institutions, great is our sin.” Charles Darwin
