<li id="c269">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55616825">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Nope, she isn't running. She's waiting. Why?</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55616825#c269?mode=alone;showrate=1#c269">7+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:947717">travelerxxx</a>, <a href="/user/uid:3419">Alexa</a>, <a href="/user/uid:57841">ivorybill</a>, <a href="/user/uid:31366">Dallasdoc</a>, <a href="/user/uid:17036">Creosote</a>, <a href="/user/uid:116838">elwior</a>, <a href="/user/uid:111992">flowerfarmer</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>It's not being coy at all. A head-on confrontation with a Hillary who hasn't an announced candidate is dumb strategy. It would look like a one-cat fight.</p>
<p>Hillary is playing it very carefully. She is trusting her spokespeople and media sycophants to keep playing up polls that show she's inevitable, invincible, ssoooo far ahead that no one could possibly catch her.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Mrs. Clinton herself is hiding away in a walled garden behind her huge council of advisers. She can't lose when she doesn't come out. And she can't make any mistakes. Pile up war chest commitments, stay unannounced so Federal reporting periods don't start to run, get her ground forces in place - all so that her eventual rolling campaign announcements will buttress the fiction that there's no one else. She will have sucked all the air out of the atmosphere.</p>
<p>What will energize others? That Hillary stumbles. Big. <u>That</u> will propel others and bleed away money and support very quickly. Which others? Some who are not running now, any more than she is.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
Ready for Warren 2016
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:199851">TRPChicago</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55616825#c269">Sun Feb 08, 2015 at 07:38:00 PM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c162">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
