<li id="c271">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55616871">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">The news is what someone says, not the truth ...</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55616871#c271?mode=alone;showrate=1#c271">6+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:327681">SixSixSix</a>, <a href="/user/uid:947717">travelerxxx</a>, <a href="/user/uid:57841">ivorybill</a>, <a href="/user/uid:31366">Dallasdoc</a>, <a href="/user/uid:116838">elwior</a>, <a href="/user/uid:62874">mightymouse</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>... of the situation.</p>
<p>That's the GOP's secret. Repeat grand themes in grand words, as few as possible and without any realistic specifics. Act like you're going on the offensive when you've said absolutely nothing tangible ... and done less. Wait for rebuttals that help make your point because then, the opponent is calling attention to what you've said, not what they stand for.</p>
<p>Works every time. The media, catering to a 15-second attention span or a read that doesn't go below the first three paragraphs (think stories in <em>US Today</em>), only has room for the What-They-Said today.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
Ready for Warren 2016
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:199851">TRPChicago</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55616871#c271">Sun Feb 08, 2015 at 07:45:07 PM PST</a></p>
