</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>starting w/ fact that, while nomination was hers to lose in 2008, she and her campaign team went about losing it. &nbsp;If someone basically blew a nomination fight that they started w/ such advantages last time, why give them the nomination this time?</p>
<p>On a substantive level, if someone is shopping around for a coherent economic policy after 22 years as a national figure, something is seriously wrong. &nbsp;Someone who got <a href="http://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/06/hillary-clintons-goldman-sachs-problem">$400k for 2 speeches to GS</a> and someone for whose super PAC Alice Walton <a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2014/02/01/ready-for-hillary-draws-big-democratic-donors/5101351/">maxed out</a> is understood by those supporters to already have an economic policy. &nbsp;The "shopping" is for a means of conning the 99% while taking care of the 1%.</p>
<p>HRC is as much of a populist as Brian Williams is a war hero.</p>

  </div>
