<li id="c318">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55619577">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Well, maybe not entirely</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55619577#c318?mode=alone;showrate=1#c318">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I don't know the details (I wish I did) but I know there are <em>some</em> voters who still buy into the old "your Representative in Congress has been sent to Congress to represent <em>you</em>" meme (or is it a trope? &nbsp;Maybe a talking point? &nbsp;I'm not too sure of <em>that</em>, either).</p>
<p>For what it's worth, <em>these</em> voters believe that they can petition their Representatives to do things for them, and get results, because their Congressperson is there to respond to <em>all</em> his or her constituents, not just the ones who voted for him.</p>
<p>Not sure how big that demographic is (call them "deluded Democrats", maybe?), but they <em>may</em> still make up a significant part of the voting public.</p>
<p>(If not, how else to explain all those people who call in to talk shows and say, "Why won't our Representatives work together to get something done?" &nbsp;Surely they're not <em>all</em> stupid. &nbsp;Surely they've heard somewhere the idea that Republican Party politics trumps the nation's welfare. &nbsp;Are they all just Republican trolls?)<br /></p>

