  <div class="ct">
  
<p>besides "soak the rich". All of us understand that income inequality is the problem. But the GOP will shift blame for wage stagnation to regulations, especially environmental regulations, and blame elites for that. They will run a populist campaign based on class - but it will pit the working class against effete college educated liberals on the coasts that hold back the dreams and pay checks of the good working people in the heartland by their unworkable environmental policies, their obsessions with race and gender, and their lack of management sense, and their love of bloated government.</p>
<p>That is a populist message. It's wrong, of course, but it is populist. The GOP will say income distribution is off, but lets remove the barriers to business so that everyone can get a job and so competition for workers will raise the wages of the deserving. It's flawed, but then again populism depends on popular support, not necessarily truth. &nbsp;Or am I misunderstanding what you mean by populism?</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
“If the misery of the poor be caused not by the laws of nature, but by our institutions, great is our sin.” Charles Darwin
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:57841">ivorybill</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55618204#c302">Mon Feb 09, 2015 at 05:40:47 AM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c76">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
