<li id="c20">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55612882">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">GOP Faux Populism</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55612882#c20?mode=alone;showrate=1#c20">11+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:308949">Phoebe Loosinhouse</a>, <a href="/user/uid:526036">starduster</a>, <a href="/user/uid:17553">Heart of the Rockies</a>, <a href="/user/uid:347248">Jake formerly of the LP</a>, <a href="/user/uid:327009">goodpractice</a>, <a href="/user/uid:116838">elwior</a>, <a href="/user/uid:62669">tallen387</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1303">cslewis</a>, <a href="/user/uid:46465">NoMoreLies</a>, <a href="/user/uid:947717">travelerxxx</a>, <a href="/user/uid:100167">Midwesterners</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>They have been doing it for years. It will work if the Democrats feel that they have to avoid the politics of "class envy". Middle class voters do not vote against Democrats because they are uncomfortable with Democrats using class issues. The only people who give a shit about it are FOX news segment producers who like to use the Democrats practicing class warfare as a go to issue. So much of the politics of Democratic strategists is to try to avoid giving material to FOX who are broadcasting to people who will never vote Democratic anyway.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig"></p>
