<li id="c25">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55613035">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">A contrarian position.</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55613035#c25?mode=alone;showrate=1#c25">10+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:77260">onionjim</a>, <a href="/user/uid:31900">pat bunny</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1638">Armando</a>, <a href="/user/uid:65037">martini</a>, <a href="/user/uid:100108">jello5929</a>, <a href="/user/uid:33131">LordMike</a>, <a href="/user/uid:3037">Phoenix Woman</a>, <a href="/user/uid:116838">elwior</a>, <a href="/user/uid:56531">Inland</a>, <a href="/user/uid:1130446">WI Lurker</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Now they're fighting on our turf. We naturally have the advantage on income inequality... "everybody knows" the GOP is the party of the rich, just as "everybody knows" the Democrats are the party of big government. It's really hard to fight those frames (just ask any Democrat who's tried to co-opt the Republican message of tax cuts and smaller government), and now we don't have to.</p>
<p>So I welcome this development. They're conceding that our issue is important. Doesn't mean we don't have to win the argument - Hillary's going to have to come up with a substantive economic plan (and yes, she can't take that for granted) - but the argument is going to be on our terms, not theirs.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:74622">DiesIrae</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55613035#c25">Sun Feb 08, 2015 at 11:09:53 AM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


