<li id="c160">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55615005">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Yes, it may happen and here is how IMHO</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55615005#c160?mode=alone;showrate=1#c160">6+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:115624">Thomas Twinnings</a>, <a href="/user/uid:307784">Portlaw</a>, <a href="/user/uid:146420">maryabein</a>, <a href="/user/uid:46465">NoMoreLies</a>, <a href="/user/uid:947717">travelerxxx</a>, <a href="/user/uid:75329">JVolvo</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Below is a portion of a comment I posted on another diary in response to Bob Johnson's question in that diary.<br /></p>
<blockquote>I also agree that Hillary will be outflanked by a Republican on economic populism. &nbsp;The outflanking maneuver will probably occur during the Republican primaries but will be used against her during the general, if she wins the Democratic nomination. I see Rand Paul leading the outflanking charge during the primaries, but not winning the Republican nomination. &nbsp;Then whomever does can use it against her.</blockquote>
Here's a big part of Hillary's problem. &nbsp;Her entire campaign strategy is to do no harm to her current status of "inevitability." &nbsp;This strategy is predicated upon two assumptions: (1) her gender identity politics will carry her with the female vote and (2) that the Republicans will have a difficult time getting someone out of the primary process who is not acceptable to the lunatic Tea Party base.
<p>The problem that strategy has been foretold in the 2014 mid term elections. &nbsp;<strong>The people want and, more importantly, need a dynamic candidate, one who is not afraid to take strong stands.</strong> &nbsp;Hillary stands for nothing as far as we have seen, particularly in the income inequality/economic arena.</p>
<p>If she cannot present a dynamic version of populism and convince the people that she means it, many of the Democratic base will stay home just as they did in 2014. &nbsp;This issue has been the 800 lb gorilla for years and the Democratic response has been to ignore it, spout platitudes, or say they are the lesser evil. &nbsp;</p>
<p>It is obvious that the lesser evil argument will not work. The people have already given the current Democratic President six years to come up with something that addresses this issue and got "grand bargains" and the catfood commission in response. &nbsp;Hillary represents more of the same. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
"I don't want to run the empire, I want to bring it down!" ~ Dr. Cornel West "...isn't the problem here that the government takes on, arbitrarily and without justification, an adversarial attitude towards its citizenry?" ~ So.Lib.inMD UID166438
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:166438">gulfgal98</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55615005#c160">Sun Feb 08, 2015 at 03:23:31 PM PST</a></p>
