<li id="c310">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55618562">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">huh?  Income inequality is what I mentioned.</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55618562#c310?mode=alone;showrate=1#c310">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:158251">jdsnebraska</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>How does a yearly 2% tax on everyone's assets address income inequality? &nbsp;That is about equalizing wealth, not income.</p>
<p>Plus it's a bad idea.<br />
Let's say a retiree managed to accumulate a million dollars worth of assets, not because he was ever part of the top 1% income earners, but by simply putting a set amount of money aside each year, earning interest on that set aside money through low risk investments (e.g. savings account interest or US bonds (yes, normal people can invest in US bonds, not just the Chinese gov't. lol)), and maybe a significant portion of that million dollars of assets is a modest house. &nbsp;And putting aside money each year entailed going without "luxuries" that his friends and neighbors indulged in like expensive consumer electronic goods, vacation trips, and whathaveyou.</p>
<p>Let's say that this retiree has a retiree friend of the same age, who annually earned <em>more</em> income, but he preferred to immediately spend his income on "luxuries" that the first retiree eschewed, such that the 2nd retiree only has accumulated $50k in assets. &nbsp;</p>
<p>So year 1 of the 2% wealth tax, the gov't seizes $20k from retiree #1 and only $1k from the retiree #2. &nbsp;You see the problem here? &nbsp;</p>
<p>Retiree #1 went without luxuries his entire life so as to put money away to live more comfortably in his retirement, while retiree #2 had higher annual income but indulged in "luxuries" rather than saving. &nbsp;So now the gov't seizes huge amounts of money from retiree #1 and hardly anything from retiree #2, despite retiree #2 having had higher annual income all his working life. &nbsp;Retiree #1 would feel like a sucker, having done without luxuries only to be punished for it. &nbsp;And that's just after the first year of the wealth tax. &nbsp;His resentment would increase with each passing year as the gov't annually seizes a huge portion of his hard earned savings.</p>
<p>I see you said 2% <em>max</em> wealth tax, so I assume someone with 1 million dollars of assets would actually be taxed less than 2% of that each year (and that the higher income'ed retiree that saved just $50k wouldn't be subject to the wealth tax at all), but the principle is still problematic. &nbsp;The gov't should not be in the business of punishing savers.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:763623">Tony Situ</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55618562#c310">Mon Feb 09, 2015 at 06:50:33 AM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c232">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


		</ul>

		</ul>





