<li id="c254">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55616396">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Consider the plot line from "Jupiter Jones."</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55616396#c254?mode=alone;showrate=1#c254">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:35014">NYFM</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>This might be a review. More a survey.</p>
<p>First off, "Jupe" starts out as an alien. The illegal kinda alien at that. No country and no father. Everybody speaks Russian.</p>
<p>Second stage, she's grown up as a Dreamer in Chicago. A toilet bowl cleaning Dreamer. Still, people speak a mix of English and Russian.</p>
<p>Third stage, her DNA gets picked up as interesting by the Abrasax clan -- intergalactic capitalists who own collections of primitive planets such as Earth.</p>
<p>-- "It's capitalism. Profits go up; shit goes down."</p>
<p>-- "Some lives are more important than others."</p>
<p>-- "There is one commodity. Time."</p>
<p>-- "They want another life. We can give that."</p>
<p>The plot connects capitalism with high-tech "harvesting."</p>
<p>It's clear early on from the first scene with the Abrasax heirs that whole planets are "harvested."</p>
<p><strong>It's capitalism.</strong> Technology gives a bloody route to immortality and it's good ol' Robber Baron madness brought to the fight -- a pinch of Roman murder-rage to add spice.</p>
<p>-- In the end, she's back cleaning toilets. It's not what you might think. Had to happen.</p>
<p>Don't expect to see corporate MSM say anything good about "Jupiter Rising."</p>
<p>Like most of us, the Wachowskis believe in small- and mid-scale capitalism. Large scale capitalism (with mergers and takeovers) and anything that gives corporations life-and-death power over people is bad news.</p>
<p>At a space opera level, "Jupiter Rising" is as dense as Shakespeare's histories. Helluva set of runs in the dialogue. If you can stay glued to dialogue flow for 2 hours and 7 minutes, you'll have a shot at getting all of it first time around.</p>
<p>W.S. and parts of Charles Dickens. And new words to decode on the fly.</p>
<p><strong>This is a $186,000,000 film.</strong> They put every dime of it on the screen. Top line, cream of the crop for England's acting corps. Plus Mila Kunis as Jupiter, Tatum Channing as the all-time bad ass dog-man.</p>
<p>Kunis flaunts her first-language Russian. Born in Ukraine.</p>
<p>Prediction: this is going to go like another very-high-demands 2014 film: "Edge of Tomorrow." Big, big hit in the brilliant countries: China, Japan, South Korea. Scored for $250,000,000 outside the U.S. Only did $100,000,000 inside the U.S.</p>
<p>"Jupiter" could do $350,000,000 outside the U.S. Become a worldwide classic.</p>
<p>If you're going to go, plan to see "Jupiter Rising" twice with a couple days between to let it settle in. Sure, the high level plot is a fairy tale. Then the details take you to a different universe and the beating heart of capitalism spurts blood at your eyes.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig">
"What the big gun lovers are doing is idolatry. It is a false religion, un-Christian. Their worship of 2nd Amendment firearms slaughters as many innocents in America as ISIL kills in the Levant."
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:676348">waterstreet2008</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55616396#c254">Sun Feb 08, 2015 at 06:31:47 PM PST</a></p>
