<li id="c311">

  <div class="cx" id="cx55618698">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Could Hillary be outflanked?  Certainly</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1363137/55618698#c311?mode=alone;showrate=1#c311">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:304786">Dr Swig Mcjigger</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>She's gotten outflanked before.</p>
<p>That said, most of what we are hearing from the GOP isn't new. &nbsp;Outside places like Texas, Republicans never run as moustache-twirling Randian capitalists, telling the hoi polloi that their duty is to suffer exploitation at the hands of their industrial betters, who have earned the right to mistreat them. &nbsp;The standard line is what is being peddled here--if the working class is in misery, it's all the fault of a) the poor, b) the government, c) the unions, and d) immigrants.</p>
<p>What is a bit unusual is to hear Republicans talking about the 1%. &nbsp;This could be dangerous for Democrats, if the GOP can actually neutralize this as an issue. &nbsp;Or, it could backfire spectacularly. &nbsp;Why?</p>
<p>a) Any cursory examination of the 1% (and in particular, the 0.1%) shows that this is an overwhelmingly GOP crowd, that favors GOP policies. &nbsp;</p>
<p>b) The whole point of the 1% meme is that the game is rigged in favor of the wealthy--and it's hard to argue that stronger unions, a stronger social safety net, and other policies of the American left (such as it is) are transferring wealth to the 1%. &nbsp; The longstanding GOP economic argument is that a race to the bottom is necessary, as the rich are Randian superheroes without whose money and industry the nation will fall apart--and American workers won't get good jobs unless the US can compete with China in terms of low wages and regulations--the social safety net and such drive capitalists away. &nbsp; OWS and the 1% framing rejected that view.</p>
<p>Every time some Republican floats some political trial balloon, it seems there is a whole host of folks here is to respond that we are all doomed doomed doomed. &nbsp;</p>
<p>At any rate, none of the current GOP crowd should be able to credibly run to Hillary's left--most of them have an established paper trail of right-wing economics that even Clinton, in her most money-sucking Third Way pandering mode, wouldn't touch with a ten foot pole. &nbsp;</p>
<p>But that doesn't mean they wont try.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:183149">EngineerScotty</a> on <a href="/comments/1363137/55618698#c311">Mon Feb 09, 2015 at 07:11:25 AM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	






